'''Sashi P. Reddi''' born on 27 May 1965 in Madras ([[Chennai]]) is an Indian [[entrepreneur]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/info-tech/article2896728.ece |title=Serial entrepreneur turns investor}}</ref> technologist and [[angel investor]].

He was the founder and CEO of AppLabs,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csc.com/independent_testing_services|date=September 15, 2011|title=APPLABS IS NOW CSC}}</ref> a [[software testing]] company based in [[Philadelphia]], [[US]] which was acquired by [[Computer Sciences Corporation]] (NYSE: CSC) in September 2011,.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entrepreneurindia.in/people/coverstory/applabs/5268/ |title=AppLabs}}</ref> At the time of the acquisition, AppLabs had over 2,500 people in [[India]], US, and [[UK]] and served many leading companies in [[financial services]], [[travel]], [[retail]], and [[technology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-09-15/news/30160094_1_applabs-csc-india-president-testing-firm |title=CSC Acquires IT testing firm AppLabs}}</ref> Post acquisition, Reddi took over the leadership of the Independent Testing Services division within CSC and in September 2012 was elevated to lead CSC's [[big data]] and [[analytics]] business.

In 2007 Reddi also founded SRI Capital, a seed stage [[venture capital]] fund focused on start-ups in [[India]], the [[US]], and the [[UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/sashi-reddi-to-invest-rs-100-cr-in-start-ups/479269/ |title=Sashi Reddi to invest Rs 100 cr in start-ups}}</ref> SRI Capital focuses on venture investments in technology, [[education]] and the [[green technology]] sectors.

==Early life and education==
Reddi completed a BTech (Computer Sciences) from [[IIT Delhi]] and went to [[New York University]] for an MS in [[Computer Science]].<ref name=testmag/> He then attended the [[Wharton School of Business]], [[University of Pennsylvania]] from where he acquired a [[PhD]] in Operations and Information Management.<ref name=testmag/> Today, Reddi serves on the advisory board of the Wharton Entrepreneurial Programs and the advisory board of IIT Hyderabad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entrepreneurship.wharton.upenn.edu/boardofadvisors.html |title=Wharton Entrepreneurship Advisory Board}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=May 2013}}

Reddi's research articles have been published in leading journals{{which|date=May 2013}} and he is a regular speaker at industry events.{{which|date=May 2013}} His paper titled 'The Impact of IT on the Degree of Outsourcing, the Number of Suppliers, and the Duration' won him the best paper award at the 27th Hawaii International Conference on System Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fic.wharton.upenn.edu/fic/papers/95/9512.pdf |title=The Impact of I.T. on the Degree of Outsourcing, the Number of Suppliers and the Duration of Contracts}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=May 2013}}

==Career==
After graduating from Wharton with a PhD in 1994, Reddi launched his first company EZPower Systems, a developer of products for building and maintaining large-scale web applications.<ref name=testmag>{{cite web|url=http://www.testmagazine.co.uk/2010/10/offshore-testing-with-a-global-reach |title=Offshore testing with a global reach}}</ref> EZPower was acquired by DocuCorp in 1998. DocuCorp was itself later acquired by Skywire, which was then acquired by [[Oracle Corporation]].{{citation needed|date=May 2013}} EZPower technology still continues to be a part of Oracle's [[document management]] offerings.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}

Following EZPower, in 1999, Reddi founded iCoop. iCoop was an internet based [[group purchasing]] service for traditional [[cooperative]]s which filed 3 patents for online group purchasing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79279779.html |title=Sashi Reddi, chairman and chief executive officer, Icoop}}</ref>

In 2001 he founded AppLabs as a 3 person independent [[software testing]] and [[quality management]] company in a shared office space in [[Philadelphia]], which grew to 2,500 employees in the US, UK, and India.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}

In September 2004, Reddi founded FXLabs, a developer of [[video game]]s for PCs, consoles, [[MMOG]], and handhelds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/the-indian-market |title=FXLabs' CEO Sashi Reddi}}</ref>

==SRI Capital==
In 2012 Reddi founded SRI Capital, a company which is a seed stage venture capital fund serving start-ups focused on investing in India, the US, and the UK . The company invests between $250,000 to $500,000 in the seed round for a significant minority stake in ventures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-02-24/news/31095245_1_angel-network-lighting-rfid |title=Sashi Reddi, founder of SRI Capital Fund}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/info-tech/article3017137.ece |title=Mr Sashi Reddi, a serial entrepreneur and founder of SRI Capital Fund}}</ref>

==ACT==
Reddi is actively involved in philanthropic activities through ACT Charitable Trust. ACT, set up in 2006,  has been involved in community initiatives including setting up infrastructure for in need schools, running programs to improve health and nutrition for children, adopting and sponsoring underserved schools and children and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/should-csr-stand-for-citizens-social-responsibility/276396/0 |title=‘Should CSR stand for citizen’s social responsibility ?’}}</ref>

He has also adopted{{clarify|date=May 2013}} 3 schools: Madinaguda Govt. Primary School, which houses 200 students, AppLabs Government Primary School, Filmnagar, which houses 180 students, and Gopanapally Govt. Primary School, which houses 175 students.

Apart from chairing ACT, Reddi actively supports the efforts of Interplast, an international NGO which provides free [[reconstructive surgery]] for the poor in developing countries. Interplast treats children and adults with clefts, disabling burns and hand injuries.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}

In July 2012 Reddi was awarded TalentSprint Special Recognition Award for his collaboration and mentorship in the design of industry-led, just-in-time inventory management.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}} He also serves on the advisory board of the Wharton Entrepreneurial Programs,{{citation needed|date=May 2013}} the advisory board of IIT Hyderabad{{citation needed|date=May 2013}} and is a charter member of TiE Hyderabad.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}

